1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:12,026
CHAPTER 12Brute Neighbors

2
00:00:12,026 --> 00:00:16,033
Sometimes I had a companion in my fishing,who came through the village to my house

3
00:00:16,033 --> 00:00:21,439
from the other side of the town, and thecatching of the dinner was as much a social

4
00:00:21,439 --> 00:00:25,089
exercise as the eating of it.

5
00:00:25,089 --> 00:00:29,022
Hermit.I wonder what the world is doing now.

6
00:00:29,022 --> 00:00:35,057
I have not heard so much as a locust overthe sweet-fern these three hours.

7
00:00:35,057 --> 00:00:41,979
The pigeons are all asleep upon theirroosts--no flutter from them.

8
00:00:41,979 --> 00:00:47,093
Was that a farmer's noon horn which soundedfrom beyond the woods just now?

9
00:00:47,093 --> 00:00:53,049
The hands are coming in to boiled salt beefand cider and Indian bread.

10
00:00:53,049 --> 00:01:04,209
Why will men worry themselves so?He that does not eat need not work.

11
00:01:04,209 --> 00:01:07,076
I wonder how much they have reaped.

12
00:01:07,076 --> 00:01:13,065
Who would live there where a body can neverthink for the barking of Bose?

13
00:01:13,065 --> 00:01:22,016
And oh, the housekeeping! to keep brightthe devil's door-knobs, and scour his tubs

14
00:01:22,016 --> 00:01:24,062
this bright day!

15
00:01:24,062 --> 00:01:32,007
Better not keep a house.Say, some hollow tree; and then for morning

16
00:01:32,007 --> 00:01:38,054
calls and dinner-parties!Only a woodpecker tapping.

17
00:01:38,054 --> 00:01:49,061
Oh, they swarm; the sun is too warm there;they are born too far into life for me.

18
00:01:49,061 --> 00:01:53,061
I have water from the spring, and a loaf ofbrown bread on the shelf.--Hark!

19
00:01:53,061 --> 00:01:58,019
I hear a rustling of the leaves.

20
00:01:58,019 --> 00:02:06,004
Is it some ill-fed village hound yieldingto the instinct of the chase? or the lost

21
00:02:06,004 --> 00:02:12,529
pig which is said to be in these woods,whose tracks I saw after the rain?

22
00:02:12,529 --> 00:02:21,063
It comes on apace; my sumachs andsweetbriers tremble.--Eh, Mr. Poet, is it

23
00:02:21,063 --> 00:02:26,082
you?How do you like the world to-day?

24
00:02:26,082 --> 00:02:28,639
Poet.

25
00:02:28,639 --> 00:02:35,029
See those clouds; how they hang!That's the greatest thing I have seen to-

26
00:02:35,029 --> 00:02:35,749
day.

27
00:02:35,749 --> 00:02:41,749
There's nothing like it in old paintings,nothing like it in foreign lands--unless

28
00:02:41,749 --> 00:02:46,049
when we were off the coast of Spain.That's a true Mediterranean sky.

29
00:02:46,049 --> 00:02:53,016
I thought, as I have my living to get, andhave not eaten to-day, that I might go a-

30
00:02:53,016 --> 00:02:57,099
fishing.That's the true industry for poets.

31
00:02:57,099 --> 00:03:00,093
It is the only trade I have learned.

32
00:03:00,093 --> 00:03:06,071
Come, let's along.Hermit.

33
00:03:06,071 --> 00:03:11,789
I cannot resist.My brown bread will soon be gone.

34
00:03:11,789 --> 00:03:18,389
I will go with you gladly soon, but I amjust concluding a serious meditation.

35
00:03:18,389 --> 00:03:23,449
I think that I am near the end of it.Leave me alone, then, for a while.

36
00:03:23,449 --> 00:03:29,249
But that we may not be delayed, you shallbe digging the bait meanwhile.

37
00:03:29,249 --> 00:03:33,179
Angleworms are rarely to be met with inthese parts, where the soil was never

38
00:03:33,179 --> 00:03:38,589
fattened with manure; the race is nearlyextinct.

39
00:03:38,589 --> 00:03:43,002
The sport of digging the bait is nearlyequal to that of catching the fish, when

40
00:03:43,002 --> 00:03:49,679
one's appetite is not too keen; and thisyou may have all to yourself today.

41
00:03:49,679 --> 00:03:55,199
I would advise you to set in the spade downyonder among the ground-nuts, where you see

42
00:03:55,199 --> 00:03:57,449
the johnswort waving.

43
00:03:57,449 --> 00:04:03,389
I think that I may warrant you one worm toevery three sods you turn up, if you look

44
00:04:03,389 --> 00:04:07,038
well in among the roots of the grass, as ifyou were weeding.

45
00:04:07,038 --> 00:04:13,449
Or, if you choose to go farther, it willnot be unwise, for I have found the

46
00:04:13,449 --> 00:04:20,049
increase of fair bait to be very nearly asthe squares of the distances.

47
00:04:20,049 --> 00:04:21,021
Hermit alone.

48
00:04:21,021 --> 00:04:28,005
Let me see; where was I?Methinks I was nearly in this frame of

49
00:04:28,005 --> 00:04:38,062
mind; the world lay about at this angle.Shall I go to heaven or a-fishing?

50
00:04:38,062 --> 00:04:45,049
If I should soon bring this meditation toan end, would another so sweet occasion be

51
00:04:45,049 --> 00:04:51,006
likely to offer?I was as near being resolved into the

52
00:04:51,006 --> 00:04:54,065
essence of things as ever I was in my life.

53
00:04:54,065 --> 00:05:01,046
I fear my thoughts will not come back tome.

54
00:05:01,046 --> 00:05:06,034
If it would do any good, I would whistlefor them.

55
00:05:06,034 --> 00:05:11,042
When they make us an offer, is it wise tosay, We will think of it?

56
00:05:11,042 --> 00:05:21,001
My thoughts have left no track, and Icannot find the path again.

57
00:05:21,001 --> 00:05:23,006
What was it that I was thinking of?

58
00:05:23,006 --> 00:05:31,083
It was a very hazy day.I will just try these three sentences of

59
00:05:31,083 --> 00:05:39,009
Confut-see; they may fetch that state aboutagain.

60
00:05:39,009 --> 00:05:45,015
I know not whether it was the dumps or abudding ecstasy.

61
00:05:45,015 --> 00:05:49,026
Mem.There never is but one opportunity of a

62
00:05:49,026 --> 00:05:51,076
kind.

63
00:05:51,076 --> 00:05:57,002
Poet.How now, Hermit, is it too soon?

64
00:05:57,002 --> 00:06:02,067
I have got just thirteen whole ones, besideseveral which are imperfect or undersized;

65
00:06:02,067 --> 00:06:08,039
but they will do for the smaller fry; theydo not cover up the hook so much.

66
00:06:08,039 --> 00:06:12,096
Those village worms are quite too large; ashiner may make a meal off one without

67
00:06:12,096 --> 00:06:17,089
finding the skewer.Hermit.

68
00:06:17,089 --> 00:06:20,064
Well, then, let's be off.

69
00:06:20,064 --> 00:06:23,065
Shall we to the Concord?There's good sport there if the water be

70
00:06:23,065 --> 00:06:29,058
not too high.Why do precisely these objects which we

71
00:06:29,058 --> 00:06:31,008
behold make a world?

72
00:06:31,008 --> 00:06:38,086
Why has man just these species of animalsfor his neighbors; as if nothing but a

73
00:06:38,086 --> 00:06:43,025
mouse could have filled this crevice?

74
00:06:43,025 --> 00:06:50,081
I suspect that Pilpay & Co. have putanimals to their best use, for they are all

75
00:06:50,081 --> 00:06:59,012
beasts of burden, in a sense, made to carrysome portion of our thoughts.

76
00:06:59,012 --> 00:07:03,046
The mice which haunted my house were notthe common ones, which are said to have

77
00:07:03,046 --> 00:07:10,065
been introduced into the country, but awild native kind not found in the village.

78
00:07:10,065 --> 00:07:16,002
I sent one to a distinguished naturalist,and it interested him much.

79
00:07:16,002 --> 00:07:21,064
When I was building, one of these had itsnest underneath the house, and before I had

80
00:07:21,064 --> 00:07:26,068
laid the second floor, and swept out theshavings, would come out regularly at lunch

81
00:07:26,068 --> 00:07:30,026
time and pick up the crumbs at my feet.

82
00:07:30,026 --> 00:07:35,081
It probably had never seen a man before;and it soon became quite familiar, and

83
00:07:35,081 --> 00:07:39,031
would run over my shoes and up my clothes.

84
00:07:39,031 --> 00:07:44,051
It could readily ascend the sides of theroom by short impulses, like a squirrel,

85
00:07:44,051 --> 00:07:47,063
which it resembled in its motions.

86
00:07:47,063 --> 00:07:53,048
At length, as I leaned with my elbow on thebench one day, it ran up my clothes, and

87
00:07:53,048 --> 00:07:59,004
along my sleeve, and round and round thepaper which held my dinner, while I kept

88
00:07:59,004 --> 00:08:02,018
the latter close, and dodged and played at

89
00:08:02,018 --> 00:08:08,026
bopeep with it; and when at last I heldstill a piece of cheese between my thumb

90
00:08:08,026 --> 00:08:15,001
and finger, it came and nibbled it, sittingin my hand, and afterward cleaned its face

91
00:08:15,001 --> 00:08:18,089
and paws, like a fly, and walked away.

92
00:08:18,089 --> 00:08:28,027
A phoebe soon built in my shed, and a robinfor protection in a pine which grew against

93
00:08:28,027 --> 00:08:30,026
the house.

94
00:08:30,026 --> 00:08:38,229
In June the partridge (Tetrao umbellus),which is so shy a bird, led her brood past

95
00:08:38,229 --> 00:08:44,039
my windows, from the woods in the rear tothe front of my house, clucking and calling

96
00:08:44,039 --> 00:08:52,799
to them like a hen, and in all her behaviorproving herself the hen of the woods.

97
00:08:52,799 --> 00:08:57,469
The young suddenly disperse on yourapproach, at a signal from the mother, as

98
00:08:57,469 --> 00:09:04,069
if a whirlwind had swept them away, andthey so exactly resemble the dried leaves

99
00:09:04,069 --> 00:09:08,012
and twigs that many a traveler has placed

100
00:09:08,012 --> 00:09:14,299
his foot in the midst of a brood, and heardthe whir of the old bird as she flew off,

101
00:09:14,299 --> 00:09:19,026
and her anxious calls and mewing, or seenher trail her wings to attract his

102
00:09:19,026 --> 00:09:24,669
attention, without suspecting theirneighborhood.

103
00:09:24,669 --> 00:09:30,046
The parent will sometimes roll and spinround before you in such a dishabille, that

104
00:09:30,046 --> 00:09:36,038
you cannot, for a few moments, detect whatkind of creature it is.

105
00:09:36,038 --> 00:09:43,037
The young squat still and flat, oftenrunning their heads under a leaf, and mind

106
00:09:43,037 --> 00:09:48,029
only their mother's directions given from adistance, nor will your approach make them

107
00:09:48,029 --> 00:09:50,429
run again and betray themselves.

108
00:09:50,429 --> 00:09:54,075
You may even tread on them, or have youreyes on them for a minute, without

109
00:09:54,075 --> 00:09:56,719
discovering them.

110
00:09:56,719 --> 00:10:02,599
I have held them in my open hand at such atime, and still their only care, obedient

111
00:10:02,599 --> 00:10:10,299
to their mother and their instinct, was tosquat there without fear or trembling.

112
00:10:10,299 --> 00:10:15,929
So perfect is this instinct, that once,when I had laid them on the leaves again,

113
00:10:15,929 --> 00:10:20,083
and one accidentally fell on its side, itwas found with the rest in exactly the same

114
00:10:20,083 --> 00:10:22,539
position ten minutes afterward.

115
00:10:22,539 --> 00:10:31,014
They are not callow like the young of mostbirds, but more perfectly developed and

116
00:10:31,014 --> 00:10:35,359
precocious even than chickens.

117
00:10:35,359 --> 00:10:41,239
The remarkably adult yet innocentexpression of their open and serene eyes is

118
00:10:41,239 --> 00:10:46,062
very memorable.All intelligence seems reflected in them.

119
00:10:46,062 --> 00:10:55,027
They suggest not merely the purity ofinfancy, but a wisdom clarified by

120
00:10:55,027 --> 00:11:01,719
experience.Such an eye was not born when the bird was,

121
00:11:01,719 --> 00:11:07,069
but is coeval with the sky it reflects.

122
00:11:07,069 --> 00:11:14,095
The woods do not yield another such a gem.The traveller does not often look into such

123
00:11:14,095 --> 00:11:17,909
a limpid well.

124
00:11:17,909 --> 00:11:25,012
The ignorant or reckless sportsman oftenshoots the parent at such a time, and

125
00:11:25,012 --> 00:11:33,669
leaves these innocents to fall a prey tosome prowling beast or bird, or gradually

126
00:11:33,669 --> 00:11:39,719
mingle with the decaying leaves which theyso much resemble.

127
00:11:39,719 --> 00:11:44,929
It is said that when hatched by a hen theywill directly disperse on some alarm, and

128
00:11:44,929 --> 00:11:52,659
so are lost, for they never hear themother's call which gathers them again.

129
00:11:52,659 --> 00:11:57,033
These were my hens and chickens.

130
00:11:57,033 --> 00:12:02,929
It is remarkable how many creatures livewild and free though secret in the woods,

131
00:12:02,929 --> 00:12:07,859
and still sustain themselves in theneighborhood of towns, suspected by hunters

132
00:12:07,859 --> 00:12:10,269
only.

133
00:12:10,269 --> 00:12:18,088
How retired the otter manages to live here!He grows to be four feet long, as big as a

134
00:12:18,088 --> 00:12:23,239
small boy, perhaps without any human beinggetting a glimpse of him.

135
00:12:23,239 --> 00:12:31,359
I formerly saw the raccoon in the woodsbehind where my house is built, and

136
00:12:31,359 --> 00:12:35,929
probably still heard their whinnering atnight.

137
00:12:35,929 --> 00:12:41,669
Commonly I rested an hour or two in theshade at noon, after planting, and ate my

138
00:12:41,669 --> 00:12:46,779
lunch, and read a little by a spring whichwas the source of a swamp and of a brook,

139
00:12:46,779 --> 00:12:55,064
oozing from under Brister's Hill, half amile from my field.

140
00:12:55,064 --> 00:13:03,039
The approach to this was through asuccession of descending grassy hollows,

141
00:13:03,039 --> 00:13:08,179
full of young pitch pines, into a largerwood about the swamp.

142
00:13:08,179 --> 00:13:16,929
There, in a very secluded and shaded spot,under a spreading white pine, there was yet

143
00:13:16,929 --> 00:13:21,069
a clean, firm sward to sit on.

144
00:13:21,069 --> 00:13:29,549
I had dug out the spring and made a well ofclear gray water, where I could dip up a

145
00:13:29,549 --> 00:13:35,088
pailful without roiling it, and thither Iwent for this purpose almost every day in

146
00:13:35,088 --> 00:13:38,599
midsummer, when the pond was warmest.

147
00:13:38,599 --> 00:13:48,001
Thither, too, the woodcock led her brood,to probe the mud for worms, flying but a

148
00:13:48,001 --> 00:13:55,239
foot above them down the bank, while theyran in a troop beneath; but at last, spying

149
00:13:55,239 --> 00:13:57,087
me, she would leave her young and circle

150
00:13:57,087 --> 00:14:04,399
round and round me, nearer and nearer tillwithin four or five feet, pretending broken

151
00:14:04,399 --> 00:14:10,095
wings and legs, to attract my attention,and get off her young, who would already

152
00:14:10,095 --> 00:14:14,056
have taken up their march, with faint, wiry

153
00:14:14,056 --> 00:14:20,929
peep, single file through the swamp, as shedirected.

154
00:14:20,929 --> 00:14:26,959
Or I heard the peep of the young when Icould not see the parent bird.

155
00:14:26,959 --> 00:14:32,669
There too the turtle doves sat over thespring, or fluttered from bough to bough of

156
00:14:32,669 --> 00:14:39,006
the soft white pines over my head; or thered squirrel, coursing down the nearest

157
00:14:39,006 --> 00:14:43,979
bough, was particularly familiar andinquisitive.

158
00:14:43,979 --> 00:14:49,000
You only need sit still long enough in someattractive spot in the woods that all its

159
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:53,899
inhabitants may exhibit themselves to youby turns.

160
00:14:53,899 --> 00:14:57,082
I was witness to events of a less peacefulcharacter.

161
00:14:57,082 --> 00:15:04,219
One day when I went out to my wood-pile, orrather my pile of stumps, I observed two

162
00:15:04,219 --> 00:15:11,025
large ants, the one red, the other muchlarger, nearly half an inch long, and

163
00:15:11,025 --> 00:15:16,064
black, fiercely contending with oneanother.

164
00:15:16,064 --> 00:15:22,081
Having once got hold they never let go, butstruggled and wrestled and rolled on the

165
00:15:22,081 --> 00:15:25,062
chips incessantly.

166
00:15:25,062 --> 00:15:28,989
Looking farther, I was surprised to findthat the chips were covered with such

167
00:15:28,989 --> 00:15:39,589
combatants, that it was not a duellum, buta bellum, a war between two races of ants,

168
00:15:39,589 --> 00:15:49,000
the red always pitted against the black,and frequently two red ones to one black.

169
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:56,089
The legions of these Myrmidons covered allthe hills and vales in my wood-yard, and

170
00:15:56,089 --> 00:16:02,539
the ground was already strewn with the deadand dying, both red and black.

171
00:16:02,539 --> 00:16:09,279
It was the only battle which I have everwitnessed, the only battle-field I ever

172
00:16:09,279 --> 00:16:20,349
trod while the battle was raging;internecine war; the red republicans on the

173
00:16:20,349 --> 00:16:25,599
one hand, and the black imperialists on theother.

174
00:16:25,599 --> 00:16:31,329
On every side they were engaged in deadlycombat, yet without any noise that I could

175
00:16:31,329 --> 00:16:37,429
hear, and human soldiers never fought soresolutely.

176
00:16:37,429 --> 00:16:43,829
I watched a couple that were fast locked ineach other's embraces, in a little sunny

177
00:16:43,829 --> 00:16:50,599
valley amid the chips, now at noondayprepared to fight till the sun went down,

178
00:16:50,599 --> 00:16:54,000
or life went out.

179
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:59,219
The smaller red champion had fastenedhimself like a vice to his adversary's

180
00:16:59,219 --> 00:17:05,609
front, and through all the tumblings onthat field never for an instant ceased to

181
00:17:05,609 --> 00:17:09,489
gnaw at one of his feelers near the root,

182
00:17:09,489 --> 00:17:14,005
having already caused the other to go bythe board; while the stronger black one

183
00:17:14,005 --> 00:17:21,169
dashed him from side to side, and, as I sawon looking nearer, had already divested him

184
00:17:21,169 --> 00:17:24,089
of several of his members.

185
00:17:24,089 --> 00:17:30,000
They fought with more pertinacity thanbulldogs.

186
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:35,179
Neither manifested the least disposition toretreat.

187
00:17:35,179 --> 00:17:41,009
It was evident that their battle-cry was"Conquer or die."

188
00:17:41,009 --> 00:17:47,179
In the meanwhile there came along a singlered ant on the hillside of this valley,

189
00:17:47,179 --> 00:17:52,037
evidently full of excitement, who eitherhad despatched his foe, or had not yet

190
00:17:52,037 --> 00:17:55,039
taken part in the battle; probably the

191
00:17:55,039 --> 00:18:01,329
latter, for he had lost none of his limbs;whose mother had charged him to return with

192
00:18:01,329 --> 00:18:05,072
his shield or upon it.

193
00:18:05,072 --> 00:18:11,061
Or perchance he was some Achilles, who hadnourished his wrath apart, and had now come

194
00:18:11,061 --> 00:18:16,959
to avenge or rescue his Patroclus.

195
00:18:16,959 --> 00:18:22,009
He saw this unequal combat from afar--forthe blacks were nearly twice the size of

196
00:18:22,009 --> 00:18:31,049
the red--he drew near with rapid pace tillhe stood on his guard within half an inch

197
00:18:31,049 --> 00:18:34,053
of the combatants; then, watching his

198
00:18:34,053 --> 00:18:40,169
opportunity, he sprang upon the blackwarrior, and commenced his operations near

199
00:18:40,169 --> 00:18:48,047
the root of his right fore leg, leaving thefoe to select among his own members; and so

200
00:18:48,047 --> 00:18:51,079
there were three united for life, as if a

201
00:18:51,079 --> 00:18:57,709
new kind of attraction had been inventedwhich put all other locks and cements to

202
00:18:57,709 --> 00:18:59,091
shame.

203
00:18:59,091 --> 00:19:05,299
I should not have wondered by this time tofind that they had their respective musical

204
00:19:05,299 --> 00:19:11,098
bands stationed on some eminent chip, andplaying their national airs the while, to

205
00:19:11,098 --> 00:19:17,579
excite the slow and cheer the dyingcombatants.

206
00:19:17,579 --> 00:19:24,013
I was myself excited somewhat even as ifthey had been men.

207
00:19:24,013 --> 00:19:31,011
The more you think of it, the less thedifference.

208
00:19:31,011 --> 00:19:36,025
And certainly there is not the fightrecorded in Concord history, at least, if

209
00:19:36,025 --> 00:19:42,179
in the history of America, that will bear amoment's comparison with this, whether for

210
00:19:42,179 --> 00:19:48,959
the numbers engaged in it, or for thepatriotism and heroism displayed.

211
00:19:48,959 --> 00:19:54,075
For numbers and for carnage it was anAusterlitz or Dresden.

212
00:19:54,075 --> 00:19:57,074
Concord Fight!

213
00:19:57,074 --> 00:20:02,035
Two killed on the patriots' side, andLuther Blanchard wounded!

214
00:20:02,035 --> 00:20:13,549
Why here every ant was a Buttrick--"Fire!for God's sake fire!"--and thousands shared

215
00:20:13,549 --> 00:20:18,009
the fate of Davis and Hosmer.

216
00:20:18,009 --> 00:20:20,073
There was not one hireling there.

217
00:20:20,073 --> 00:20:26,041
I have no doubt that it was a principlethey fought for, as much as our ancestors,

218
00:20:26,041 --> 00:20:33,000
and not to avoid a three-penny tax on theirtea; and the results of this battle will be

219
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:35,829
as important and memorable to those whom it

220
