Second from Sweden.

259
00:24:04,089 --> 00:24:10,549
The battle which I witnessed took place inthe Presidency of Polk, five years before

260
00:24:10,549 --> 00:24:15,439
the passage of Webster's Fugitive-SlaveBill.

261
00:24:15,439 --> 00:24:22,027
Many a village Bose, fit only to course amud-turtle in a victualling cellar, sported

262
00:24:22,027 --> 00:24:27,011
his heavy quarters in the woods, withoutthe knowledge of his master, and

263
00:24:27,011 --> 00:24:29,939
ineffectually smelled at old fox burrows

264
00:24:29,939 --> 00:24:37,199
and woodchucks' holes; led perchance bysome slight cur which nimbly threaded the

265
00:24:37,199 --> 00:24:44,015
wood, and might still inspire a naturalterror in its denizens;--now far behind his

266
00:24:44,015 --> 00:24:46,099
guide, barking like a canine bull toward

267
00:24:46,099 --> 00:24:53,199
some small squirrel which had treed itselffor scrutiny, then, cantering off, bending

268
00:24:53,199 --> 00:24:58,539
the bushes with his weight, imagining thathe is on the track of some stray member of

269
00:24:58,539 --> 00:25:01,959
the jerbilla family.

270
00:25:01,959 --> 00:25:07,053
Once I was surprised to see a cat walkingalong the stony shore of the pond, for they

271
00:25:07,053 --> 00:25:14,169
rarely wander so far from home.The surprise was mutual.

272
00:25:14,169 --> 00:25:20,159
Nevertheless the most domestic cat, whichhas lain on a rug all her days, appears

273
00:25:20,159 --> 00:25:27,819
quite at home in the woods, and, by her slyand stealthy behavior, proves herself more

274
00:25:27,819 --> 00:25:33,002
native there than the regular inhabitants.

275
00:25:33,002 --> 00:25:39,052
Once, when berrying, I met with a cat withyoung kittens in the woods, quite wild, and

276
00:25:39,052 --> 00:25:44,003
they all, like their mother, had theirbacks up and were fiercely spitting at me.

277
00:25:44,003 --> 00:25:53,037
A few years before I lived in the woodsthere was what was called a "winged cat" in

278
00:25:53,037 --> 00:25:59,039
one of the farm-houses in Lincoln nearestthe pond, Mr. Gilian Baker's.

279
00:25:59,039 --> 00:26:04,059
When I called to see her in June, 1842, shewas gone a-hunting in the woods, as was her

280
00:26:04,059 --> 00:26:11,001
wont (I am not sure whether it was a maleor female, and so use the more common

281
00:26:11,001 --> 00:26:14,038
pronoun), but her mistress told me that she

282
00:26:14,038 --> 00:26:19,026
came into the neighborhood a little morethan a year before, in April, and was

283
00:26:19,026 --> 00:26:25,689
finally taken into their house; that shewas of a dark brownish-gray color, with a

284
00:26:25,689 --> 00:26:29,039
white spot on her throat, and white feet,

285
00:26:29,039 --> 00:26:36,039
and had a large bushy tail like a fox; thatin the winter the fur grew thick and

286
00:26:36,039 --> 00:26:42,088
flatted out along her sides, formingstripes ten or twelve inches long by two

287
00:26:42,088 --> 00:26:45,939
and a half wide, and under her chin like a

288
00:26:45,939 --> 00:26:53,065
muff, the upper side loose, the undermatted like felt, and in the spring these

289
00:26:53,065 --> 00:26:59,159
appendages dropped off.They gave me a pair of her "wings," which I

290
00:26:59,159 --> 00:26:59,073
keep still.

291
00:26:59,073 --> 00:27:05,709
There is no appearance of a membrane aboutthem.

292
00:27:05,709 --> 00:27:10,559
Some thought it was part flying squirrel orsome other wild animal, which is not

293
00:27:10,559 --> 00:27:16,002
impossible, for, according to naturalists,prolific hybrids have been produced by the

294
00:27:16,002 --> 00:27:20,549
union of the marten and domestic cat.

295
00:27:20,549 --> 00:27:26,022
This would have been the right kind of catfor me to keep, if I had kept any; for why

296
00:27:26,022 --> 00:27:32,159
should not a poet's cat be winged as wellas his horse?

297
00:27:32,159 --> 00:27:39,077
In the fall the loon (Colymbus glacialis)came, as usual, to moult and bathe in the

298
00:27:39,077 --> 00:27:44,319
pond, making the woods ring with his wildlaughter before I had risen.

299
00:27:44,319 --> 00:27:52,429
At rumor of his arrival all the Mill-damsportsmen are on the alert, in gigs and on

300
00:27:52,429 --> 00:27:58,559
foot, two by two and three by three, withpatent rifles and conical balls and spy-

301
00:27:58,559 --> 00:28:00,439
glasses.

302
00:28:00,439 --> 00:28:05,659
They come rustling through the woods likeautumn leaves, at least ten men to one

303
00:28:05,659 --> 00:28:07,005
loon.

304
00:28:07,005 --> 00:28:12,579
Some station themselves on this side of thepond, some on that, for the poor bird

305
00:28:12,579 --> 00:28:19,679
cannot be omnipresent; if he dive here hemust come up there.

306
00:28:19,679 --> 00:28:25,087
But now the kind October wind rises,rustling the leaves and rippling the

307
00:28:25,087 --> 00:28:32,073
surface of the water, so that no loon canbe heard or seen, though his foes sweep the

308
00:28:32,073 --> 00:28:39,085
pond with spy-glasses, and make the woodsresound with their discharges.

309
00:28:39,085 --> 00:28:46,024
The waves generously rise and dash angrily,taking sides with all water-fowl, and our

310
00:28:46,024 --> 00:28:54,037
sportsmen must beat a retreat to town andshop and unfinished jobs.

311
00:28:54,037 --> 00:28:59,189
But they were too often successful.

312
00:28:59,189 --> 00:29:03,077
When I went to get a pail of water early inthe morning I frequently saw this stately

313
00:29:03,077 --> 00:29:09,789
bird sailing out of my cove within a fewrods.

314
00:29:09,789 --> 00:29:14,689
If I endeavored to overtake him in a boat,in order to see how he would manoeuvre, he

315
00:29:14,689 --> 00:29:20,065
would dive and be completely lost, so thatI did not discover him again, sometimes,

316
00:29:20,065 --> 00:29:23,829
till the latter part of the day.

317
00:29:23,829 --> 00:29:27,299
But I was more than a match for him on thesurface.

318
00:29:27,299 --> 00:29:31,015
He commonly went off in a rain.

319
00:29:31,015 --> 00:29:38,001
As I was paddling along the north shore onevery calm October afternoon, for such days

320
00:29:38,001 --> 00:29:44,289
especially they settle on to the lakes,like the milkweed down, having looked in

321
00:29:44,289 --> 00:29:47,309
vain over the pond for a loon, suddenly

322
00:29:47,309 --> 00:29:53,709
one, sailing out from the shore toward themiddle a few rods in front of me, set up

323
00:29:53,709 --> 00:30:00,099
his wild laugh and betrayed himself.I pursued with a paddle and he dived, but

324
00:30:00,099 --> 00:30:04,059
when he came up I was nearer than before.

325
00:30:04,059 --> 00:30:10,059
He dived again, but I miscalculated thedirection he would take, and we were fifty

326
00:30:10,059 --> 00:30:15,929
rods apart when he came to the surface thistime, for I had helped to widen the

327
00:30:15,929 --> 00:30:22,799
interval; and again he laughed long andloud, and with more reason than before.

328
00:30:22,799 --> 00:30:31,014
He manoeuvred so cunningly that I could notget within half a dozen rods of him.

329
00:30:31,014 --> 00:30:35,809
Each time, when he came to the surface,turning his head this way and that, he

330
00:30:35,809 --> 00:30:42,159
cooly surveyed the water and the land, andapparently chose his course so that he

331
00:30:42,159 --> 00:30:44,024
might come up where there was the widest

332
00:30:44,024 --> 00:30:49,529
expanse of water and at the greatestdistance from the boat.

333
00:30:49,529 --> 00:30:53,419
It was surprising how quickly he made uphis mind and put his resolve into

334
00:30:53,419 --> 00:30:55,086
execution.

335
00:30:55,086 --> 00:31:00,329
He led me at once to the widest part of thepond, and could not be driven from it.

336
00:31:00,329 --> 00:31:05,064
While he was thinking one thing in hisbrain, I was endeavoring to divine his

337
00:31:05,064 --> 00:31:07,899
thought in mine.

338
00:31:07,899 --> 00:31:17,014
It was a pretty game, played on the smoothsurface of the pond, a man against a loon.

339
00:31:17,014 --> 00:31:20,829
Suddenly your adversary's checkerdisappears beneath the board, and the

340
00:31:20,829 --> 00:31:26,529
problem is to place yours nearest to wherehis will appear again.

341
00:31:26,529 --> 00:31:30,048
Sometimes he would come up unexpectedly onthe opposite side of me, having apparently

342
00:31:30,048 --> 00:31:33,399
passed directly under the boat.

343
00:31:33,399 --> 00:31:39,051
So long-winded was he and so unweariable,that when he had swum farthest he would

344
00:31:39,051 --> 00:31:46,439
immediately plunge again, nevertheless; andthen no wit could divine where in the deep

345
00:31:46,439 --> 00:31:49,084
pond, beneath the smooth surface, he might

346
00:31:49,084 --> 00:31:56,001
be speeding his way like a fish, for he hadtime and ability to visit the bottom of the

347
00:31:56,001 --> 00:31:59,013
pond in its deepest part.

348
00:31:59,013 --> 00:32:05,023
It is said that loons have been caught inthe New York lakes eighty feet beneath the

349
00:32:05,023 --> 00:32:13,029
surface, with hooks set for trout--thoughWalden is deeper than that.

350
00:32:13,029 --> 00:32:18,929
How surprised must the fishes be to seethis ungainly visitor from another sphere

351
00:32:18,929 --> 00:32:23,069
speeding his way amid their schools!

352
00:32:23,069 --> 00:32:27,649
Yet he appeared to know his course assurely under water as on the surface, and

353
00:32:27,649 --> 00:32:31,024
swam much faster there.

354
00:32:31,024 --> 00:32:35,087
Once or twice I saw a ripple where heapproached the surface, just put his head

355
00:32:35,087 --> 00:32:40,072
out to reconnoitre, and instantly divedagain.

356
00:32:40,072 --> 00:32:46,014
I found that it was as well for me to reston my oars and wait his reappearing as to

357
00:32:46,014 --> 00:32:51,076
endeavor to calculate where he would rise;for again and again, when I was straining

358
00:32:51,076 --> 00:32:54,036
my eyes over the surface one way, I would

359
00:32:54,036 --> 00:33:00,569
suddenly be startled by his unearthly laughbehind me.

360
00:33:00,569 --> 00:33:06,939
But why, after displaying so much cunning,did he invariably betray himself the moment

361
00:33:06,939 --> 00:33:11,049
he came up by that loud laugh?

362
00:33:11,049 --> 00:33:19,062
Did not his white breast enough betray him?He was indeed a silly loon, I thought.

363
00:33:19,062 --> 00:33:24,063
I could commonly hear the splash of thewater when he came up, and so also detected

364
00:33:24,063 --> 00:33:25,076
him.

365
00:33:25,076 --> 00:33:31,539
But after an hour he seemed as fresh asever, dived as willingly, and swam yet

366
00:33:31,539 --> 00:33:34,579
farther than at first.

367
00:33:34,579 --> 00:33:40,000
It was surprising to see how serenely hesailed off with unruffled breast when he

368
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:45,089
came to the surface, doing all the workwith his webbed feet beneath.

369
00:33:45,089 --> 00:33:56,036
His usual note was this demoniac laughter,yet somewhat like that of a water-fowl; but

370
00:33:56,036 --> 00:34:01,779
occasionally, when he had balked me mostsuccessfully and come up a long way off, he

371
00:34:01,779 --> 00:34:06,077
uttered a long-drawn unearthly howl,

372
00:34:06,077 --> 00:34:12,069
probably more like that of a wolf than anybird; as when a beast puts his muzzle to

373
00:34:12,069 --> 00:34:17,029
the ground and deliberately howls.

374
00:34:17,029 --> 00:34:24,029
This was his looning--perhaps the wildestsound that is ever heard here, making the

375
00:34:24,029 --> 00:34:30,088
woods ring far and wide.I concluded that he laughed in derision of

376
00:34:30,088 --> 00:34:35,017
my efforts, confident of his own resources.

377
00:34:35,017 --> 00:34:41,016
Though the sky was by this time overcast,the pond was so smooth that I could see

378
00:34:41,016 --> 00:34:45,019
where he broke the surface when I did nothear him.

379
00:34:45,019 --> 00:34:49,729
His white breast, the stillness of the air,and the smoothness of the water were all

380
00:34:49,729 --> 00:34:52,012
against him.

381
00:34:52,012 --> 00:34:58,709
At length having come up fifty rods off, heuttered one of those prolonged howls, as if

382
00:34:58,709 --> 00:35:06,005
calling on the god of loons to aid him, andimmediately there came a wind from the east

383
00:35:06,005 --> 00:35:08,029
and rippled the surface, and filled the

384
00:35:08,029 --> 00:35:14,034
whole air with misty rain, and I wasimpressed as if it were the prayer of the

385
00:35:14,034 --> 00:35:23,058
loon answered, and his god was angry withme; and so I left him disappearing far away

386
00:35:23,058 --> 00:35:25,018
on the tumultuous surface.

387
00:35:25,018 --> 00:35:32,092
For hours, in fall days, I watched theducks cunningly tack and veer and hold the

388
00:35:32,092 --> 00:35:39,085
middle of the pond, far from the sportsman;tricks which they will have less need to

389
00:35:39,085 --> 00:35:43,239
practise in Louisiana bayous.

390
00:35:43,239 --> 00:35:49,032
When compelled to rise they would sometimescircle round and round and over the pond at

391
00:35:49,032 --> 00:35:53,007
a considerable height, from which theycould easily see to other ponds and the

392
00:35:53,007 --> 00:35:58,042
river, like black motes in the sky; and,

393
00:35:58,042 --> 00:36:03,054
when I thought they had gone off thitherlong since, they would settle down by a

394
00:36:03,054 --> 00:36:10,088
slanting flight of a quarter of a mile onto a distant part which was left free; but

395
00:36:10,088 --> 00:36:13,088
what beside safety they got by sailing in

396
00:36:13,088 --> 00:36:21,016
the middle of Walden I do not know, unlessthey love its water for the same reason

397
00:36:21,016 --> 00:36:28,004
that I do.

398
