420
00:38:35,439 --> 00:38:38,075
Occasionally I climbed and shook the trees.

421
00:38:38,075 --> 00:38:45,639
They grew also behind my house, and onelarge tree, which almost overshadowed it,

422
00:38:45,639 --> 00:38:51,069
was, when in flower, a bouquet whichscented the whole neighborhood, but the

423
00:38:51,069 --> 00:38:53,016
squirrels and the jays got most of its

424
00:38:53,016 --> 00:38:59,066
fruit; the last coming in flocks early inthe morning and picking the nuts out of the

425
00:38:59,066 --> 00:39:06,609
burs before they fell, I relinquished thesetrees to them and visited the more distant

426
00:39:06,609 --> 00:39:09,003
woods composed wholly of chestnut.

427
00:39:09,003 --> 00:39:11,003
These nuts, as far as they went, were agood substitute for bread.

428
00:39:11,003 --> 00:39:15,056
Many other substitutes might, perhaps, befound.

429
00:39:15,056 --> 00:39:21,009
Digging one day for fishworms, I discoveredthe ground-nut (Apios tuberosa) on its

430
00:39:21,009 --> 00:39:28,099
string, the potato of the aborigines, asort of fabulous fruit, which I had begun

431
00:39:28,099 --> 00:39:31,699
to doubt if I had ever dug and eaten in

432
00:39:31,699 --> 00:39:36,077
childhood, as I had told, and had notdreamed it.

