It has a sweetish taste, much like that ofa frost-bitten potato, and I found it

437
00:39:56,078 --> 00:39:59,069
better boiled than roasted.

438
00:39:59,069 --> 00:40:04,091
This tuber seemed like a faint promise ofNature to rear her own children and feed

439
00:40:04,091 --> 00:40:07,379
them simply here at some future period.

440
00:40:07,379 --> 00:40:15,046
In these days of fatted cattle and wavinggrain-fields this humble root, which was

441
00:40:15,046 --> 00:40:22,044
once the totem of an Indian tribe, is quiteforgotten, or known only by its flowering

442
00:40:22,044 --> 00:40:27,043
vine; but let wild Nature reign here once

443
00:40:27,043 --> 00:40:33,077
more, and the tender and luxurious Englishgrains will probably disappear before a

444
00:40:33,077 --> 00:40:39,097
myriad of foes, and without the care of manthe crow may carry back even the last seed

445
00:40:39,097 --> 00:40:42,077
of corn to the great cornfield of the

446
00:40:42,077 --> 00:40:49,031
Indian's God in the southwest, whence he issaid to have brought it; but the now almost

447
00:40:49,031 --> 00:40:56,006
exterminated ground-nut will perhaps reviveand flourish in spite of frosts and

448
00:40:56,006 --> 00:41:00,009
wildness, prove itself indigenous, and

449
00:41:00,009 --> 00:41:07,072
resume its ancient importance and dignityas the diet of the hunter tribe.

450
00:41:07,072 --> 00:41:15,002
Some Indian Ceres or Minerva must have beenthe inventor and bestower of it; and when

451
00:41:15,002 --> 00:41:20,068
the reign of poetry commences here, itsleaves and string of nuts may be

452
00:41:20,068 --> 00:41:25,004
represented on our works of art.

453
00:41:25,004 --> 00:41:29,099
Already, by the first of September, I hadseen two or three small maples turned

454
00:41:29,099 --> 00:41:37,065
scarlet across the pond, beneath where thewhite stems of three aspens diverged, at

455
00:41:37,065 --> 00:41:40,033
the point of a promontory, next the water.

456
00:41:40,033 --> 00:41:47,099
Ah, many a tale their color told!And gradually from week to week the

457
00:41:47,099 --> 00:41:53,072
character of each tree came out, and itadmired itself reflected in the smooth

458
00:41:53,072 --> 00:41:56,016
mirror of the lake.

459
00:41:56,016 --> 00:42:02,074
Each morning the manager of this gallerysubstituted some new picture, distinguished

460
00:42:02,074 --> 00:42:10,007
by more brilliant or harmonious coloring,for the old upon the walls.

461
00:42:10,007 --> 00:42:16,079
The wasps came by thousands to my lodge inOctober, as to winter quarters, and settled

462
00:42:16,079 --> 00:42:22,049
on my windows within and on the wallsoverhead, sometimes deterring visitors from

463
00:42:22,049 --> 00:42:23,093
entering.

464
00:42:23,093 --> 00:42:30,004
Each morning, when they were numbed withcold, I swept some of them out, but I did

465
00:42:30,004 --> 00:42:35,039
not trouble myself much to get rid of them;I even felt complimented by their regarding

466
00:42:35,039 --> 00:42:38,009
my house as a desirable shelter.

467
00:42:38,009 --> 00:42:44,043
They never molested me seriously, thoughthey bedded with me; and they gradually

468
00:42:44,043 --> 00:42:53,071
disappeared, into what crevices I do notknow, avoiding winter and unspeakable cold.

469
00:42:53,071 --> 00:42:59,066
Like the wasps, before I finally went intowinter quarters in November, I used to

470
00:42:59,066 --> 00:43:05,048
resort to the northeast side of Walden,which the sun, reflected from the pitch

471
00:43:05,048 --> 00:43:08,038
pine woods and the stony shore, made the

472
00:43:08,038 --> 00:43:13,789
fireside of the pond; it is so muchpleasanter and wholesomer to be warmed by

473
00:43:13,789 --> 00:43:17,043
the sun while you can be, than by anartificial fire.

474
00:43:17,043 --> 00:43:24,051
I thus warmed myself by the still glowingembers which the summer, like a departed

475
00:43:24,051 --> 00:43:30,051
hunter, had left.When I came to build my chimney I studied

476
00:43:30,051 --> 00:43:31,093
masonry.

477
00:43:31,093 --> 00:43:37,061
My bricks, being second-hand ones, requiredto be cleaned with a trowel, so that I

478
00:43:37,061 --> 00:43:42,052
learned more than usual of the qualities ofbricks and trowels.

479
00:43:42,052 --> 00:43:48,008
The mortar on them was fifty years old, andwas said to be still growing harder; but

480
00:43:48,008 --> 00:43:53,069
this is one of those sayings which men loveto repeat whether they are true or not.

481
00:43:53,069 --> 00:43:59,083
Such sayings themselves grow harder andadhere more firmly with age, and it would

482
00:43:59,083 --> 00:44:06,001
take many blows with a trowel to clean anold wiseacre of them.

483
00:44:06,001 --> 00:44:10,094
Many of the villages of Mesopotamia arebuilt of second-hand bricks of a very good

484
00:44:10,094 --> 00:44:16,086
quality, obtained from the ruins ofBabylon, and the cement on them is older

485
00:44:16,086 --> 00:44:20,036
and probably harder still.

486
00:44:20,036 --> 00:44:25,077
However that may be, I was struck by thepeculiar toughness of the steel which bore

487
00:44:25,077 --> 00:44:30,044
so many violent blows without being wornout.

488
00:44:30,044 --> 00:44:35,096
As my bricks had been in a chimney before,though I did not read the name of

489
00:44:35,096 --> 00:44:42,086
Nebuchadnezzar on them, I picked out asmany fireplace bricks as I could find, to

490
00:44:42,086 --> 00:44:45,043
save work and waste, and I filled the

491
00:44:45,043 --> 00:44:50,056
spaces between the bricks about thefireplace with stones from the pond shore,

492
00:44:50,056 --> 00:44:57,027
and also made my mortar with the white sandfrom the same place.

493
00:44:57,027 --> 00:45:03,669
I lingered most about the fireplace, as themost vital part of the house.

494
00:45:03,669 --> 00:45:09,061
Indeed, I worked so deliberately, thatthough I commenced at the ground in the

495
00:45:09,061 --> 00:45:14,092
morning, a course of bricks raised a fewinches above the floor served for my pillow

496
00:45:14,092 --> 00:45:18,067
at night; yet I did not get a stiff neck

497
00:45:18,067 --> 00:45:24,003
for it that I remember; my stiff neck is ofolder date.

498
00:45:24,003 --> 00:45:31,036
I took a poet to board for a fortnightabout those times, which caused me to be

499
00:45:31,036 --> 00:45:34,002
put to it for room.

500
00:45:34,002 --> 00:45:39,058
He brought his own knife, though I had two,and we used to scour them by thrusting them

501
00:45:39,058 --> 00:45:44,025
into the earth.He shared with me the labors of cooking.

502
00:45:44,025 --> 00:45:51,001
I was pleased to see my work rising sosquare and solid by degrees, and reflected,

503
00:45:51,001 --> 00:45:58,065
that, if it proceeded slowly, it wascalculated to endure a long time.

504
00:45:58,065 --> 00:46:02,088
The chimney is to some extent anindependent structure, standing on the

505
00:46:02,088 --> 00:46:09,047
ground, and rising through the house to theheavens; even after the house is burned it

506
00:46:09,047 --> 00:46:15,679
still stands sometimes, and its importanceand independence are apparent.

507
00:46:15,679 --> 00:46:21,091
This was toward the end of summer.It was now November.

508
00:46:21,091 --> 00:46:26,083
The north wind had already begun to coolthe pond, though it took many weeks of

509
00:46:26,083 --> 00:46:30,004
steady blowing to accomplish it, it is sodeep.

510
00:46:30,004 --> 00:46:36,054
When I began to have a fire at evening,before I plastered my house, the chimney

511
00:46:36,054 --> 00:46:42,072
carried smoke particularly well, because ofthe numerous chinks between the boards.

512
00:46:42,072 --> 00:46:48,085
Yet I passed some cheerful evenings in thatcool and airy apartment, surrounded by the

513
00:46:48,085 --> 00:46:55,083
rough brown boards full of knots, andrafters with the bark on high overhead.

514
00:46:55,083 --> 00:47:01,064
My house never pleased my eye so much afterit was plastered, though I was obliged to

515
00:47:01,064 --> 00:47:04,098
confess that it was more comfortable.

516
00:47:04,098 --> 00:47:09,064
Should not every apartment in which mandwells be lofty enough to create some

517
00:47:09,064 --> 00:47:15,045
obscurity overhead, where flickeringshadows may play at evening about the

518
00:47:15,045 --> 00:47:17,065
rafters?

519
00:47:17,065 --> 00:47:22,051
These forms are more agreeable to the fancyand imagination than fresco paintings or

520
00:47:22,051 --> 00:47:28,084
other the most expensive furniture.

521
00:47:28,084 --> 00:47:36,429
I now first began to inhabit my house, Imay say, when I began to use it for warmth

522
00:47:36,429 --> 00:47:39,015
as well as shelter.

523
00:47:39,015 --> 00:47:44,549
I had got a couple of old fire-dogs to keepthe wood from the hearth, and it did me

524
00:47:44,549 --> 00:47:51,015
good to see the soot form on the back ofthe chimney which I had built, and I poked

525
00:47:51,015 --> 00:47:55,095
the fire with more right and moresatisfaction than usual.

526
00:47:55,095 --> 00:48:01,096
My dwelling was small, and I could hardlyentertain an echo in it; but it seemed

527
00:48:01,096 --> 00:48:06,089
larger for being a single apartment andremote from neighbors.

528
00:48:06,089 --> 00:48:12,009
All the attractions of a house wereconcentrated in one room; it was kitchen,

529
00:48:12,009 --> 00:48:18,049
chamber, parlor, and keeping-room; andwhatever satisfaction parent or child,

530
00:48:18,049 --> 00:48:24,064
master or servant, derive from living in ahouse, I enjoyed it all.

531
00:48:24,064 --> 00:48:31,077
Cato says, the master of a family(patremfamilias) must have in his rustic

532
00:48:31,077 --> 00:48:44,023
villa "cellam oleariam, vinariam, doliamulta, uti lubeat caritatem expectare, et

533
00:48:44,023 --> 00:48:51,002
rei, et virtuti, et gloriae erit," that is,

534
00:48:51,002 --> 00:48:56,095
"an oil and wine cellar, many casks, sothat it may be pleasant to expect hard

535
00:48:56,095 --> 00:49:03,095
times; it will be for his advantage, andvirtue, and glory."

536
00:49:03,095 --> 00:49:11,062
I had in my cellar a firkin of potatoes,about two quarts of peas with the weevil in

537
00:49:11,062 --> 00:49:18,084
them, and on my shelf a little rice, a jugof molasses, and of rye and Indian meal a

538
00:49:18,084 --> 00:49:19,062
peck each.

539
00:49:19,062 --> 00:49:27,076
I sometimes dream of a larger and morepopulous house, standing in a golden age,

540
00:49:27,076 --> 00:49:33,179
of enduring materials, and withoutgingerbread work, which shall still consist

541
00:49:33,179 --> 00:49:37,013
of only one room, a vast, rude,

542
00:49:37,013 --> 00:49:44,058
substantial, primitive hall, withoutceiling or plastering, with bare rafters

543
00:49:44,058 --> 00:49:50,078
and purlins supporting a sort of lowerheaven over one's head--useful to keep off

544
00:49:50,078 --> 00:49:53,073
rain and snow, where the king and queen

545
00:49:53,073 --> 00:49:59,000
posts stand out to receive your homage,when you have done reverence to the

546
00:49:59,000 --> 00:50:06,046
prostrate Saturn of an older dynasty onstepping over the sill; a cavernous house,

547
00:50:06,046 --> 00:50:09,001
wherein you must reach up a torch upon a

548
00:50:09,001 --> 00:50:15,035
pole to see the roof; where some may livein the fireplace, some in the recess of a

549
00:50:15,035 --> 00:50:22,033
window, and some on settles, some at oneend of the hall, some at another, and some

550
00:50:22,033 --> 00:50:25,047
aloft on rafters with the spiders, if they

551
00:50:25,047 --> 00:50:33,013
choose; a house which you have got intowhen you have opened the outside door, and

552
00:50:33,013 --> 00:50:38,919
the ceremony is over; where the wearytraveller may wash, and eat, and converse,

553
00:50:38,919 --> 00:50:43,071
and sleep, without further journey; such a

554
00:50:43,071 --> 00:50:50,002
shelter as you would be glad to reach in atempestuous night, containing all the

555
00:50:50,002 --> 00:50:56,076
essentials of a house, and nothing forhouse-keeping; where you can see all the

556
00:50:56,076 --> 00:50:59,044
treasures of the house at one view, and

557
00:50:59,044 --> 00:51:05,489
everything hangs upon its peg, that a manshould use; at once kitchen, pantry,

558
00:51:05,489 --> 00:51:13,419
parlor, chamber, storehouse, and garret;where you can see so necessary a thing, as

559
00:51:13,419 --> 00:51:17,002
a barrel or a ladder, so convenient a thing

560
00:51:17,002 --> 00:51:22,032
as a cupboard, and hear the pot boil, andpay your respects to the fire that cooks

561
00:51:22,032 --> 00:51:27,057
your dinner, and the oven that bakes yourbread, and the necessary furniture and

562
00:51:27,057 --> 00:51:31,419
utensils are the chief ornaments; where the

563
00:51:31,419 --> 00:51:37,044
washing is not put out, nor the fire, northe mistress, and perhaps you are sometimes

564
00:51:37,044 --> 00:51:42,008
requested to move from off the trap-door,when the cook would descend into the

565
00:51:42,008 --> 00:51:44,095
cellar, and so learn whether the ground is

566
00:51:44,095 --> 00:51:48,489
solid or hollow beneath you withoutstamping.

567
00:51:48,489 --> 00:51:55,077
A house whose inside is as open andmanifest as a bird's nest, and you cannot

568
00:51:55,077 --> 00:52:03,007
go in at the front door and out at the backwithout seeing some of its inhabitants;

569
00:52:03,007 --> 00:52:06,049
where to be a guest is to be presented with

570
00:52:06,049 --> 00:52:11,075
the freedom of the house, and not to becarefully excluded from seven eighths of

571
00:52:11,075 --> 00:52:17,005
it, shut up in a particular cell, and toldto make yourself at home there--in solitary

572
00:52:17,005 --> 00:52:19,739
confinement.

573
00:52:19,739 --> 00:52:25,007
Nowadays the host does not admit you to hishearth, but has got the mason to build one

574
00:52:25,007 --> 00:52:31,919
for yourself somewhere in his alley, andhospitality is the art of keeping you at

575
00:52:31,919 --> 00:52:33,007
the greatest distance.

576
00:52:33,007 --> 00:52:41,057
There is as much secrecy about the cookingas if he had a design to poison you.

577
00:52:41,057 --> 00:52:47,034
I am aware that I have been on many a man'spremises, and might have been legally

578
00:52:47,034 --> 00:52:55,072
ordered off, but I am not aware that I havebeen in many men's houses.

579
00:52:55,072 --> 00:53:02,003
I might visit in my old clothes a king andqueen who lived simply in such a house as I

580
00:53:02,003 --> 00:53:07,076
have described, if I were going their way;but backing out of a modern palace will be

581
00:53:07,076 --> 00:53:13,239
all that I shall desire to learn, if ever Iam caught in one.

582
00:53:13,239 --> 00:53:20,002
It would seem as if the very language ofour parlors would lose all its nerve and

583
00:53:20,002 --> 00:53:26,169
degenerate into palaver wholly, our livespass at such remoteness from its symbols,

584
00:53:26,169 --> 00:53:28,859
and its metaphors and tropes are

585
00:53:28,859 --> 00:53:35,549
necessarily so far fetched, through slidesand dumb-waiters, as it were; in other

586
00:53:35,549 --> 00:53:39,819
words, the parlor is so far from thekitchen and workshop.

587
00:53:39,819 --> 00:53:47,539
The dinner even is only the parable of adinner, commonly.

588
00:53:47,539 --> 00:53:53,579
As if only the savage dwelt near enough toNature and Truth to borrow a trope from

589
00:53:53,579 --> 00:53:55,509
them.

590
00:53:55,509 --> 00:54:02,949
How can the scholar, who dwells away in theNorth West Territory or the Isle of Man,

591
00:54:02,949 --> 00:54:07,819
tell what is parliamentary in the kitchen?

592
00:54:07,819 --> 00:54:13,062
However, only one or two of my guests wereever bold enough to stay and eat a hasty-

593
00:54:13,062 --> 00:54:19,829
pudding with me; but when they saw thatcrisis approaching they beat a hasty

594
00:54:19,829 --> 00:54:25,088
retreat rather, as if it would shake thehouse to its foundations.

595
00:54:25,088 --> 00:54:32,049
Nevertheless, it stood through a great manyhasty-puddings.

596
00:54:32,049 --> 00:54:37,169
I did not plaster till it was freezingweather.

597
00:54:37,169 --> 00:54:43,001
I brought over some whiter and cleaner sandfor this purpose from the opposite shore of

598
00:54:43,001 --> 00:54:48,000
the pond in a boat, a sort of conveyancewhich would have tempted me to go much

599
00:54:48,000 --> 00:54:50,939
farther if necessary.

600
00:54:50,939 --> 00:54:55,048
My house had in the meanwhile been shingleddown to the ground on every side.

601
00:54:55,048 --> 00:55:02,073
In lathing I was pleased to be able to sendhome each nail with a single blow of the

602
00:55:02,073 --> 00:55:07,075
hammer, and it was my ambition to transferthe plaster from the board to the wall

603
00:55:07,075 --> 00:55:09,059
neatly and rapidly.

604
00:55:09,059 --> 00:55:15,006
I remembered the story of a conceitedfellow, who, in fine clothes, was wont to

605
00:55:15,006 --> 00:55:20,048
lounge about the village once, givingadvice to workmen.

606
00:55:20,048 --> 00:55:26,009
Venturing one day to substitute deeds forwords, he turned up his cuffs, seized a

607
00:55:26,009 --> 00:55:31,389
plasterer's board, and having loaded histrowel without mishap, with a complacent

608
00:55:31,389 --> 00:55:33,949
look toward the lathing overhead, made a

609
00:55:33,949 --> 00:55:40,709
bold gesture thitherward; and straightway,to his complete discomfiture, received the

610
00:55:40,709 --> 00:55:44,759
whole contents in his ruffled bosom.

611
00:55:44,759 --> 00:55:50,679
I admired anew the economy and convenienceof plastering, which so effectually shuts

612
00:55:50,679 --> 00:55:56,072
out the cold and takes a handsome finish,and I learned the various casualties to

613
00:55:56,072 --> 00:55:59,098
which the plasterer is liable.

614
00:55:59,098 --> 00:56:04,389
I was surprised to see how thirsty thebricks were which drank up all the moisture

615
00:56:04,389 --> 00:56:09,759
in my plaster before I had smoothed it, andhow many pailfuls of water it takes to

616
00:56:09,759 --> 00:56:12,035
christen a new hearth.

617
00:56:12,035 --> 00:56:17,409
I had the previous winter made a smallquantity of lime by burning the shells of

618
00:56:17,409 --> 00:56:24,012
the Unio fluviatilis, which our riveraffords, for the sake of the experiment; so

619
00:56:24,012 --> 00:56:27,075
that I knew where my materials came from.

620
00:56:27,075 --> 00:56:32,779
I might have got good limestone within amile or two and burned it myself, if I had

621
00:56:32,779 --> 00:56:33,439
cared to do so.

622
00:56:33,439 --> 00:56:40,199
The pond had in the meanwhile skimmed overin the shadiest and shallowest coves, some

623
00:56:40,199 --> 00:56:43,879
days or even weeks before the generalfreezing.

624
00:56:43,879 --> 00:56:51,139
The first ice is especially interesting andperfect, being hard, dark, and transparent,

625
00:56:51,139 --> 00:56:55,919
and affords the best opportunity that everoffers for examining the bottom where it is

626
00:56:55,919 --> 00:56:59,189
shallow; for you can lie at your length on

627
00:56:59,189 --> 00:57:05,949
ice only an inch thick, like a skaterinsect on the surface of the water, and

628
00:57:05,949 --> 00:57:11,209
study the bottom at your leisure, only twoor three inches distant, like a picture

629
00:57:11,209 --> 00:57:17,059
behind a glass, and the water isnecessarily always smooth then.

630
00:57:17,059 --> 00:57:22,259
There are many furrows in the sand wheresome creature has travelled about and

631
00:57:22,259 --> 00:57:30,899
doubled on its tracks; and, for wrecks, itis strewn with the cases of caddis-worms

632
00:57:30,899 --> 00:57:35,559
made of minute grains of white quartz.

633
00:57:35,559 --> 00:57:41,009
Perhaps these have creased it, for you findsome of their cases in the furrows, though

634
00:57:41,009 --> 00:57:45,001
they are deep and broad for them to make.

635
00:57:45,001 --> 00:57:50,047
But the ice itself is the object of mostinterest, though you must improve the

636
00:57:50,047 --> 00:57:52,309
earliest opportunity to study it.

637
00:57:52,309 --> 00:58:00,649
If you examine it closely the morning afterit freezes, you find that the greater part

638
00:58:00,649 --> 00:58:08,029
of the bubbles, which at first appeared tobe within it, are against its under

639
00:58:08,029 --> 00:58:11,879
surface, and that more are continually

640
00:58:11,879 --> 00:58:19,048
rising from the bottom; while the ice is asyet comparatively solid and dark, that is,

641
00:58:19,048 --> 00:58:22,409
you see the water through it.

642
00:58:22,409 --> 00:58:29,509
These bubbles are from an eightieth to aneighth of an inch in diameter, very clear

643
00:58:29,509 --> 00:58:35,779
and beautiful, and you see your facereflected in them through the ice.

644
00:58:35,779 --> 00:58:40,209
There may be thirty or forty of them to asquare inch.

645
00:58:40,209 --> 00:58:46,919
There are also already within the icenarrow oblong perpendicular bubbles about

646
00:58:46,919 --> 00:58:54,079
half an inch long, sharp cones with theapex upward; or oftener, if the ice is

647
00:58:54,079 --> 00:58:58,309
quite fresh, minute spherical bubbles one

648
00:58:58,309 --> 00:59:02,035
directly above another, like a string ofbeads.

649
00:59:02,035 --> 00:59:08,539
But these within the ice are not sonumerous nor obvious as those beneath.

650
00:59:08,539 --> 00:59:14,319
I sometimes used to cast on stones to trythe strength of the ice, and those which

651
00:59:14,319 --> 00:59:20,034
broke through carried in air with them,which formed very large and conspicuous

652
00:59:20,034 --> 00:59:23,029
white bubbles beneath.

