812
01:13:57,051 --> 01:14:02,078
window and see if the house was not onfire; it was the only time I remember to

813
01:14:02,078 --> 01:14:05,081
have been particularly anxious on this

814
01:14:05,081 --> 01:14:13,036
score; so I looked and saw that a spark hadcaught my bed, and I went in and

815
01:14:13,036 --> 01:14:18,064
extinguished it when it had burned a placeas big as my hand.

816
01:14:18,064 --> 01:14:24,015
But my house occupied so sunny andsheltered a position, and its roof was so

817
01:14:24,015 --> 01:14:30,004
low, that I could afford to let the fire goout in the middle of almost any winter day.

818
01:14:30,004 --> 01:14:37,019
The moles nested in my cellar, nibblingevery third potato, and making a snug bed

819
01:14:37,019 --> 01:14:43,007
even there of some hair left afterplastering and of brown paper; for even the

820
01:14:43,007 --> 01:14:45,047
wildest animals love comfort and warmth as

821
01:14:45,047 --> 01:14:51,018
well as man, and they survive the winteronly because they are so careful to secure

822
01:14:51,018 --> 01:14:56,005
them.Some of my friends spoke as if I was coming

823
01:14:56,005 --> 01:14:59,065
to the woods on purpose to freeze myself.

824
01:14:59,065 --> 01:15:06,044
The animal merely makes a bed, which hewarms with his body, in a sheltered place;

825
01:15:06,044 --> 01:15:12,041
but man, having discovered fire, boxes upsome air in a spacious apartment, and warms

826
01:15:12,041 --> 01:15:16,029
that, instead of robbing himself, makes

827
01:15:16,029 --> 01:15:22,027
that his bed, in which he can move aboutdivested of more cumbrous clothing,

828
01:15:22,027 --> 01:15:29,001
maintain a kind of summer in the midst ofwinter, and by means of windows even admit

829
01:15:29,001 --> 01:15:33,089
the light, and with a lamp lengthen out theday.

830
01:15:33,089 --> 01:15:40,071
